`new findings`
- HH/HL + VWAP gate vastly improves ORB results


Best Approach
The clean version of your idea is:

Define regimes first, independently of strategy PnL.
Build specialist strategies for each regime.
Only deploy a strategy when its regime is active.
Evaluate the portfolio EV of accounts, not the beauty of each backtest.
So for example:

Bull regime: trend-continuation, breakout, ORB continuation
Bear regime: fast downside continuation, failed auction, rejection / breakdown
Sideways regime: mean reversion, fade extremes, lower RR / shorter holding

Practical Framework
I’d structure it like this:

Layer 1: Regime classifier
bull / bear / sideways
based on simple observable features:
higher timeframe trend
realized volatility
range expansion / contraction
breadth / index behavior if you use it
Layer 2: Specialist strategy
each strategy is built only for one regime
Layer 3: Account portfolio
multiple accounts running different specialists or different activation rules
Layer 4: Kill switch
if live stats deviate too far from expected behavior, disable quickly

For your use case, even simpler is better:

trend state
volatility state
intraday participation state
That gives you a regime grid like:

trending + high vol
trending + low vol
non-trending + low vol
non-trending + high vol

How to evaluate it
This is the most important part.

If the real business model is prop-firm payout extraction, your main metric should not be just Sharpe or full-history Calmar. It should be something like:

expected payout per account attempt
first payout probability
average number of resets before payout
average payout multiple vs account cost
time to payout
correlation of failure across accounts
live decay rate after deployment
A strategy that is “fragile but explosive” may be perfectly acceptable if:

challenge cost is cheap
payout is large
you can run enough independent attempts
losers are not too correlated

Layer 1: Regime classifier
Layer 2: Specialist strategy
Layer 3: Account portfolio
Layer 4: Kill switch